## 4. Keyboard-Driven TUI Workflow Patterns

### Vim-Like Modal Navigation

The canonical modal state machine:

```rust
#[derive(Clone, Copy, PartialEq, Eq, Debug, Default)]
enum Mode {
    #[default]
    Normal,     // navigation, no text input
    Insert,     // text input active
    Command,    // : prefix command mode
    Visual,     // selection mode
}

struct App {
    mode: Mode,
    command_buffer: String,
    // ... other state
}

impl App {
    fn handle_key(&mut self, key: KeyEvent) -> Option<Action> {
        match self.mode {
            Mode::Normal => self.handle_normal_key(key),
            Mode::Insert => self.handle_insert_key(key),
            Mode::Command => self.handle_command_key(key),
            Mode::Visual => self.handle_visual_key(key),
        }
    }

    fn handle_normal_key(&mut self, key: KeyEvent) -> Option<Action> {
        match key.code {
            KeyCode::Char('i') => { self.mode = Mode::Insert; None }
            KeyCode::Char(':') => { self.mode = Mode::Command; None }
            KeyCode::Char('j') | KeyCode::Down => Some(Action::MoveDown),
            KeyCode::Char('k') | KeyCode::Up   => Some(Action::MoveUp),
            KeyCode::Char('g') => Some(Action::MoveTop),
            KeyCode::Char('G') => Some(Action::MoveBottom),
            KeyCode::Esc => Some(Action::Quit),
            _ => None,
        }
    }
}
```

The mode is always displayed to the user in a status bar (left-aligned, fixed position).

### Leader-Key Sequences

The `ctrl+x` or `space` leader key pattern:

```rust
#[derive(Clone, Copy, PartialEq, Eq, Debug)]
enum InputState {
    Normal,
    AwaitingLeader,  // leader key pressed, waiting for second key
}

struct KeybindRouter {
    state: InputState,
    leader: KeyCode,
}

impl KeybindRouter {
    fn process(&mut self, key: KeyEvent) -> Option<Command> {
        match self.state {
            InputState::Normal => {
                if key.code == self.leader {
                    self.state = InputState::AwaitingLeader;
                    None
                } else {
                    self.dispatch_normal(key)
                }
            }
            InputState::AwaitingLeader => {
                self.state = InputState::Normal;
                self.dispatch_leader_chord(key)
            }
        }
    }

    fn dispatch_leader_chord(&self, key: KeyEvent) -> Option<Command> {
        match key.code {
            KeyCode::Char('n') => Some(Command::NewSession),
            KeyCode::Char('l') => Some(Command::ListSessions),
            KeyCode::Char('g') => Some(Command::Timeline),
            KeyCode::Char('x') => Some(Command::Export),
            _ => None,
        }
    }
}
```

For multi-step chords (like `ctrl+k → ctrl+p` in VS Code), extend to a trie:
```rust
struct ChordTrie {
    children: HashMap<KeyEvent, ChordNode>,
}
enum ChordNode {
    Command(Command),
    Branch(ChordTrie),
}
```

### Command Palette Pattern

The VS Code-style command palette uses fuzzy matching + keybinding display:

```rust
struct CommandPalette {
    open: bool,
    query: String,
    commands: Vec<Command>,  // registered commands
    filtered: Vec<usize>,    // indices into commands
    selected: usize,
}

struct Command {
    id: &'static str,
    title: &'static str,
    keybind: Option<&'static str>,   // display string e.g. "ctrl+p"
    hidden: bool,
    action: fn(&mut App),
}

impl CommandPalette {
    fn filter(&mut self) {
        self.filtered = self.commands.iter().enumerate()
            .filter(|(_, cmd)| !cmd.hidden && fuzzy_match(&self.query, cmd.title))
            .map(|(i, _)| i)
            .collect();
    }
}
```

Open with `ctrl+p`, type to filter, arrow keys to navigate, Enter to execute, Esc to close.

Render pattern: overlay a centered floating box over the main UI using `Clear` widget + `Block`:
```rust
fn render_command_palette(palette: &CommandPalette, frame: &mut Frame) {
    let area = centered_rect(60, 40, frame.area());
    frame.render_widget(Clear, area);  // clear background
    let block = Block::bordered().title("Commands");
    // render palette content inside block
}
```

### Context-Sensitive Keybinding Display

The "status bar shows current keys" pattern - display a dynamic hint bar at the bottom that changes based on active mode/context:

```rust
fn render_keybind_hints(mode: Mode, frame: &mut Frame, area: Rect) {
    let hints = match mode {
        Mode::Normal => vec![
            ("[j/k]", "navigate"),
            ("[Enter]", "select"),
            ("[:]", "command"),
            ("[?]", "help"),
        ],
        Mode::Insert => vec![
            ("[Esc]", "normal mode"),
            ("[Tab]", "complete"),
