## 5. Screen Navigation State Machines

### Enum-Based FSM (Simple Apps)

The minimal viable screen router:

```rust
#[derive(Clone, PartialEq, Eq, Hash, Debug)]
enum Screen {
    Dashboard,
    Plans,
    PlanDetail(String),  // carries context
    Config,
    Help,
}

struct App {
    screen: Screen,
    history: Vec<Screen>,  // for "back" navigation
}

impl App {
    fn navigate_to(&mut self, screen: Screen) {
        let prev = std::mem::replace(&mut self.screen, screen);
        self.history.push(prev);
    }

    fn navigate_back(&mut self) {
        if let Some(prev) = self.history.pop() {
            self.screen = prev;
        }
    }

    fn handle_event(&mut self, event: Event) {
        match &self.screen {
            Screen::Dashboard => self.handle_dashboard_event(event),
            Screen::Plans => self.handle_plans_event(event),
            Screen::PlanDetail(id) => {
                let id = id.clone();
                self.handle_detail_event(event, &id)
            },
            Screen::Config => self.handle_config_event(event),
            Screen::Help => {
                if matches!(event, Event::Key(k) if k.code == KeyCode::Esc) {
                    self.navigate_back();
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
```

### Hierarchical State Machine with statig

For complex navigation with superstates, `statig` (crates.io) provides the Harel statechart model:

```toml
[dependencies]
statig = { version = "0.3", features = ["async"] }
```

```rust
use statig::prelude::*;

#[derive(Default)]
struct TuiApp { /* shared context */ }

#[derive(Clone, Debug, PartialEq)]
enum State {
    Dashboard,
    Plans,
    PlanDetail,
    Config,
    Modal,
}

#[derive(Clone, Debug)]
enum Event {
    KeyPress(KeyCode),
    Tick,
    DataLoaded,
}

// statig macro-based implementation
#[state_machine(
    initial = "State::Dashboard",
    state(derive(Clone, Debug, PartialEq)),
    superstate(derive(Clone, Debug)),
)]
impl TuiApp {
    // Dashboard is the default root
    #[state(superstate = "navigable")]
    async fn dashboard(event: &Event) -> Outcome<State> {
        match event {
            Event::KeyPress(KeyCode::Char('p')) => Transition(State::Plans),
            Event::KeyPress(KeyCode::Char('c')) => Transition(State::Config),
            _ => Super,
        }
    }

    #[state(superstate = "navigable")]
    async fn plans(event: &Event) -> Outcome<State> {
        match event {
            Event::KeyPress(KeyCode::Enter) => Transition(State::PlanDetail),
            _ => Super,
        }
    }

    // Superstate: shared behavior for all navigable screens
    #[superstate]
    async fn navigable(event: &Event) -> Outcome<State> {
        match event {
            Event::KeyPress(KeyCode::Esc) => Transition(State::Dashboard),
            Event::KeyPress(KeyCode::Char('?')) => Transition(State::Modal),
            Event::KeyPress(KeyCode::Char('q')) => { /* quit */ Handled }
            _ => Super,
        }
    }

    // Modal overlaid on top: defer unhandled events back
    #[state(entry_action = "enter_modal", exit_action = "exit_modal")]
    async fn modal(event: &Event) -> Outcome<State> {
        match event {
            Event::KeyPress(KeyCode::Esc) => Transition(State::Dashboard), // or history
            _ => Handled, // consume all input while modal is open (focus trap)
        }
    }

    #[action]
    fn enter_modal(&mut self) { /* save focus context */ }

    #[action]
    fn exit_modal(&mut self) { /* restore focus context */ }
}
```

Key statig behaviors:
- `Outcome::Super` - defer event to parent superstate (avoids duplicating Esc handling in every screen)
- `Outcome::Transition(State::X)` - move to new state
- `Outcome::Handled` - consume event without state change
- Entry/exit `#[action]` functions fire on every transition through that state
- State-local storage: data specific to a state lives only while that state is active
- `handle_with_context()` passes `&mut AppContext` to all handlers

### Focus Ring Management

The `ratatui-interact` crate provides `FocusManager<T>`:

```rust
use ratatui_interact::FocusManager;

struct PanelState {
    focus: FocusManager<PanelId>,
}

#[derive(Clone, PartialEq, Eq)]
enum PanelId {
    Sidebar,
    Main,
    DetailPane,
}

impl PanelState {
    fn new() -> Self {
        let mut focus = FocusManager::new();
        focus.register(PanelId::Sidebar);
        focus.register(PanelId::Main);
        focus.register(PanelId::DetailPane);
        Self { focus }
    }

    fn handle_key(&mut self, key: KeyCode) {
        match key {
            KeyCode::Tab       => self.focus.next(),
            KeyCode::BackTab   => self.focus.prev(),
            _ => {}
        }
    }
}
```

Alternatively, `rat-focus` (from the rat-salsa ecosystem) uses a builder pattern rebuilt each event:

```rust
// Built fresh every event loop - no stale state
let focus = FocusBuilder::new()
    .widget(&sidebar)
    .widget(&main_panel)
    .widget(&detail_pane)
    .build();

// Navigate
focus.next();
focus.prev();
focus.focus_at(&mouse_position);

// Query
if sidebar.is_focused() { /* render with highlight */ }
```

### Modal Overlay State Management

The correct pattern for modals is to model them as a layer in the state, not a separate screen:

```rust
struct App {
    screen: Screen,           // base screen always renders
    modal: Option<Modal>,     // overlay renders on top when Some
}

enum Modal {
    Help,
    Confirm { message: String, on_confirm: fn(&mut App) },
    CommandPalette(PaletteState),
}

fn handle_key(app: &mut App, key: KeyEvent) {
    // Modal captures all input when active (focus trap)
    if let Some(modal) = &mut app.modal {
        match modal {
            Modal::Help => {
                if key.code == KeyCode::Esc { app.modal = None; }
            }
            Modal::Confirm { on_confirm, .. } => {
                match key.code {
                    KeyCode::Char('y') => { on_confirm(app); app.modal = None; }
                    KeyCode::Esc | KeyCode::Char('n') => { app.modal = None; }
                    _ => {}
                }
            }
            _ => { /* delegate to modal's own handler */ }
        }
        return;  // IMPORTANT: return here to prevent base layer from receiving input
    }
    // Base screen handles input only when no modal is active
    match app.screen { /* ... */ }
}

fn render(app: &App, frame: &mut Frame) {
    render_base_screen(&app.screen, frame);  // always render base
    if let Some(modal) = &app.modal {
        render_modal(modal, frame);  // overlay on top
    }
}
```

For rendering overlays, use `ratatui`'s `Clear` widget plus a centered rect helper:

```rust
fn centered_rect(percent_x: u16, percent_y: u16, area: Rect) -> Rect {
    let [_, center, _] = Layout::vertical([
        Percentage((100 - percent_y) / 2),
        Percentage(percent_y),
        Percentage((100 - percent_y) / 2),
    ]).areas(area);
    let [_, center, _] = Layout::horizontal([
        Percentage((100 - percent_x) / 2),
        Percentage(percent_x),
        Percentage((100 - percent_x) / 2),
    ]).areas(center);
    center
}

// Usage
frame.render_widget(Clear, overlay_area);  // erase background
frame.render_widget(modal_widget, overlay_area);
```

### Breadcrumb Trail for Nested Navigation

```rust
struct NavigationContext {
    breadcrumbs: Vec<BreadcrumbEntry>,
}

struct BreadcrumbEntry {
    label: String,
    screen: Screen,
}

fn render_breadcrumb(ctx: &NavigationContext, frame: &mut Frame, area: Rect) {
    let spans: Vec<Span> = ctx.breadcrumbs.iter().enumerate().flat_map(|(i, entry)| {
        let is_last = i == ctx.breadcrumbs.len() - 1;
        if is_last {
            vec![Span::styled(&entry.label, Style::default().bold())]
        } else {
            vec![
                Span::raw(&entry.label),
                Span::styled(" > ", Style::default().dim()),
            ]
        }
    }).collect();
    frame.render_widget(Line::from(spans), area);
}
